<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">from the Porcupine Mountain of which I Shall Speak Shortly, to <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> bottom of the great black bay which <span class="DelHand-author">joins</span> <span class="AddHand-author">approaches</span> the Hudsons bay Territor<span class="DelHand-author">y</span><span class="AddHand-author">ie</span>s on the Opposite Side the distance cannot be less than from 120 to 130 leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The greatest length of Lake Superior is Reckoned from Metal toad Cape to what french call Fond du Lac, or the Bottom of the Lake which I am certain is not less than 150 Leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  When to this vast surface is added the unrival<span class="AddHand-author">l</span>ed purity of the water and its great depth (which was tried by the Captain of the N.W. C<sup>os</sup> Vessel off the Pique in 1793 with 600 fathom of cord but no bottom) it must be allowed the Superiority over all the inland waters yet discovered<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">But to Return to the Anse, the Western side is chiefly Basaltes and as usual, presents in general a convex Smooth Surface to the water<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  There is a line of Mountains which Runs from the Portage to the point, a distance of twelve leagues<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They are mostly Conical, One of them is very large and considerably elevated, and the next to it has the appearance of an Oblong Square, the Summit of which looks precisely like a Table<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  And here I cannot help again digressing to attempt the description of a Phenomenon which 'tho perhaps</p>

